03971nam a22005175i 9780773567825DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19991999xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735678257 a10.1515/97807735678252doi  a(DE-B1597)656509  a(OCoLC)741349714  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHB3530.S25 ǂb G68 1999eb 7aHIS0060002bisacsh04a304.6/09714/5231 aGossage, Peter, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFamilies in Transition :bIndustry and Population in Nineteenth-Century Saint-Hyacynthe /cPeter Gossage. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1999] 4c©1999  a1 online resource (344 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies on the History of Quebec/Études d'histoire du Québec ;v1100tFront Matter -- tContents -- tTables -- tFigures -- tPreface -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tSaint-Hyacinthe in Context -- tGenesis of an Industrial Town -- tTo Have and to Hold: Marriage and Family Formation in Nineteenth-Century Saint-Hyacinthe -- tFamilies at the Threshold: Newlyweds, Household Structure, and Proximity to Kin -- tInteresting Conditions: Fertility and Family Size in Transition -- tConclusion: The Art of the Possible -- tFamily Formation in Focus: An Essay on Methods -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGossage uses a family-reconstitution method, drawing on local parish registers and manuscript-census schedules, to focus on marriage, household organization, and family size in this context of social and economic change. Family formation was profoundly affected as couples adjusted to the new urban, industrial setting. Gossage demonstrates that demographic behaviour was increasingly differentiated by social class, with distinct marriage and fertility patterns emerging among bourgeois and proletarian families. Bourgeois women who married in the 1860s, for example, were already limiting family size, a crucial shift that did not occur in working-class families until almost a generation later. Families in Transition demonstrates the extent to which stereotypes about family life in Quebec before the Quiet Revolution need to be revisited. Far from being passive, static, uniformly prolific, and constrained by religious and cultural perspectives, Saint-Hyacinthe families responded quickly to the changing realities of the day, reinventing marriage patterns and domestic arrangements to fit the new industrial capitalism of the nineteenth century. In this sense they were truly families in transition.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356782540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773567825423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773567825/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles